{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17631081","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17631081"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T17:22:28+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T17:22:28+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17348"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17348","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17348"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.59,0.05,0,0.14,0.23]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10038"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114358"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10038","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10038"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17348"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96359"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"6733"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23500"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23503"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23518"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114358","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/114358"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe lymphatic drainage of the stomach is clinically important for understanding the spread of gastric cancer.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the primary direction of lymphatic drainage from this organ?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["To coeliac lymph nodes","To inferior mesenteric lymph nodes","To internal iliac lymph nodes","Directly to thoracic duct","To superior mesenteric lymph nodes"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe lymphatic drainage of the stomach primarily flows to the \u003Cstrong\u003Ecoeliac lymph nodes\u003C/strong\u003E. This occurs via four main groups of lymph nodes that receive drainage from different regions of the stomach: the left and right gastric nodes (along lesser curvature) and the left and right gastroepiploic nodes (along greater curvature).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELymph must first pass through regional nodes before reaching the \u003Cstrong\u003Ethoracic duct\u003C/strong\u003E directly. The \u003Cstrong\u003Esuperior mesenteric lymph nodes\u003C/strong\u003E primarily drain the small intestine and proximal large bowel rather than the stomach. The \u003Cstrong\u003Einternal iliac lymph nodes\u003C/strong\u003E drain the pelvic organs rather than abdominal organs like the stomach. The \u003Cstrong\u003Einferior mesenteric lymph nodes\u003C/strong\u003E primarily drain the distal large bowel and do not receive gastric lymphatic drainage. Understanding this pattern of drainage is crucial for predicting the likely path of metastatic spread in gastric cancer and for planning surgical management.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The stomach\u0027s lymphatic drainage follows four main pathways: along the left and right gastric vessels and along the left and right gastroepiploic vessels.","Most lymphatic drainage from the stomach ultimately flows to the coeliac lymph nodes.","Lymphatics from the lesser curvature follow the left and right gastric vessels while those from the greater curvature follow the gastroepiploic vessels."],"references":["Netter FH. Netter Atlas of Human Anatomy: A Regional Approach with Latin Terminology. Eighth edition. Elsevier; 2022.","Drake R. Gray\u0027s Atlas of Anatomy. 3rd ed. Elsevier Health Sciences; 2021."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96359"}},"question"